    <h1 class="place-title">The Chindi</h1>
    <p class="place-subtitle">Rumor File — something that should have moved on, and didn't.</p>

    <img class="place-img"
         src="{{ url_for('static', filename='placeholders/chindi.jpg') }}"
         alt="The Chindi placeholder">

    <p>
      In Navajo tradition, the chindi is what remains when a person dies — not the whole of them,
      but the dark residue. The parts that could not be reconciled. Most pass on. Some do not.
      Those that linger are not mourned. They are avoided.
    </p>

    <p>
      What has been reported in the area is not a figure. It is an absence. A shape that appears
      in still water, in glass, in anything reflective — there for a moment, and gone before the
      eye can fix on it. Those who have seen it describe a shadow with no source. A silhouette
      that does not match anything in the room.
    </p>

    <p>
      One account describes an image in a bathroom mirror — a person standing in water that wasn't
      there. When the witness moved closer, the image was gone. What replaced it was a cold that
      had no explanation, and a feeling of being watched by something that could not look away.
    </p>

    <p>
      Mirrors and still water have long been understood in Southwestern tradition as thresholds.
      Places where the boundary between the living world and whatever lies beyond it grows thin.
      Most of the time, nothing crosses. Most of the time.
    </p>

    <p>
      The chindi does not pursue. It does not threaten. It simply remains — fixed to a place it
      cannot leave, caught in a passage it cannot complete. Whether it is dangerous is a matter
      of some debate among those who take such things seriously. What is not debated is this:
      it should not still be here.
    </p>

